\f1\b\fs48 \cf0 \strokec2 The Impact of Home Blood Pressure Monitoring on Blood Pressure Control in Patients With Essential Hypertension: A Randomized Controlled Study\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 Abstract\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Background:
\f0\b0  Hypertension is a leading modifiable risk factor for cardiovascular morbidity and mortality worldwide. Despite the availability of effective antihypertensive medications, blood pressure control rates remain suboptimal. Home blood pressure monitoring (HBPM) has been proposed as an adjunct to standard care to improve patient engagement and treatment outcomes.\

\f1\b Objective:
\f0\b0  To evaluate the effectiveness of HBPM combined with standard care compared to standard care alone in improving blood pressure control among patients with essential hypertension.\

\f1\b Methods:
\f0\b0  A 6-month randomized controlled trial was conducted involving 160 adults with diagnosed essential hypertension. Participants were randomly assigned to either an intervention group receiving HBPM plus standard care or a control group receiving standard care alone. Primary outcomes included changes in systolic and diastolic blood pressure. Secondary outcomes included medication adherence, patient satisfaction, and frequency of antihypertensive therapy adjustments.\

\f1\b Results:
\f0\b0  At 6 months, the intervention group demonstrated a significantly greater reduction in systolic and diastolic blood pressure compared to the control group (\uc0\u8722 14.6/\u8722 8.9 mmHg vs. \u8722 7.2/\u8722 4.1 mmHg; p < 0.001). Medication adherence and patient satisfaction scores were significantly higher in the HBPM group. No serious adverse events were reported.\

\f1\b Conclusion:
\f0\b0  The addition of HBPM to standard care significantly improves blood pressure control, medication adherence, and patient satisfaction in individuals with essential hypertension. HBPM should be considered a valuable component of hypertension management strategies.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Introduction\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Hypertension affects more than 1.2 billion individuals globally and is a major contributor to cardiovascular disease, stroke, renal failure, and premature mortality. Despite advances in pharmacological therapy and clinical guidelines, effective blood pressure control remains elusive for a substantial proportion of patients. Factors such as poor medication adherence, inadequate treatment intensification, and limited patient engagement contribute to suboptimal outcomes.\
Traditional blood pressure measurement in clinical settings has several limitations, including white-coat hypertension, masked hypertension, and variability due to measurement conditions. These factors can lead to misclassification and inappropriate treatment decisions. Home blood pressure monitoring (HBPM) offers a practical and accessible alternative that allows for repeated measurements in a familiar environment, potentially providing more accurate representations of a patient\'92s true blood pressure.\
Previous observational studies and meta-analyses suggest that HBPM may improve blood pressure control and adherence to antihypertensive therapy. However, variability in study design and patient populations has limited the generalizability of findings. Furthermore, data from randomized controlled trials in routine clinical practice settings remain limited.\
The present study aims to evaluate the effectiveness of HBPM as an adjunct to standard care in improving blood pressure control in patients with essential hypertension.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
