\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Discussion\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 This randomized controlled study demonstrates that HBPM significantly improves blood pressure control in patients with essential hypertension when combined with standard care. The magnitude of blood pressure reduction observed in the HBPM group is clinically meaningful and associated with a reduced risk of cardiovascular events.\
Several mechanisms may explain these findings. HBPM likely enhances patient awareness and engagement, leading to improved medication adherence and lifestyle modifications. Additionally, more frequent blood pressure data may facilitate timely and accurate treatment adjustments by clinicians.\
The improved adherence observed in this study aligns with previous research suggesting that patient involvement in self-monitoring fosters a sense of ownership over disease management. Increased patient satisfaction further supports the acceptability of HBPM in routine care.\
Limitations of this study include its single-center design and relatively short follow-up period. Future studies should assess long-term outcomes, cost-effectiveness, and integration of digital health platforms for remote data transmission.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Conclusion\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Home blood pressure monitoring, when combined with standard care, significantly improves blood pressure control, medication adherence, and patient satisfaction in patients with essential hypertension. These findings support the routine incorporation of HBPM into hypertension management strategies to improve clinical outcomes.\
